// 📦 SUMMARY  
// This code builds: A Jenkins Declarative Pipeline that loads an external Groovy helper script and uses it to build, test, and deploy an application based on pipeline parameters.  
// Language/Platform: Jenkins Declarative Pipeline (Groovy syntax)  
// What you'll learn: Loading external Groovy scripts, conditional stage execution with parameters, using global variables, calling script functions.  
// Outcome: Jenkins pipeline executes build, test (optional), and deploy stages, calling corresponding functions from the loaded Groovy script and passing parameters where needed.  
// Why this matters: Modularizes pipeline logic for better maintainability and reusability, while enabling dynamic pipeline control via parameters.  

def gv  // ✅ What it does: Declares a global variable to hold the loaded external Groovy script.  
        // 🧠 Why it matters: Needed so functions from the script can be accessed throughout the pipeline stages.  

pipeline {  
  agent any  // ✅ What it does: Runs the pipeline on any available Jenkins agent.  
             // 🧠 Why it matters: Provides flexibility to run on any node without restrictions.  

  parameters {  
    choice(  
      name: 'VERSION',           // ✅ What it does: Parameter to select the app version to build/deploy.  
      choices: ['v1', 'v2', 'v3'],  // ✅ Options for the app version.  
      description: 'Select app version'  // ✅ Description shown in Jenkins UI to guide users.  
    )  
    booleanParam(  
      name: 'executeTests',       // ✅ What it does: Boolean parameter to decide whether to run tests.  
      defaultValue: true,         // ✅ Default is to run tests if user does not change.  
      description: 'Run Tests?'   // ✅ Description in UI for clarity.  
    )  
  }  

  stages {  
    stage('Init') {  
      steps {  
        script {  
          gv = load 'script.groovy'  // ✅ What it does: Loads external Groovy helper script into global variable gv.  
                                    // 🧠 Why it matters: Allows pipeline to call reusable functions defined in the external script.  
        }  
      }  
    }  

    stage('Build') {  
      steps {  
        script {  
          echo "Building version ${params.VERSION}"  // ✅ What it does: Logs the version being built.  
                                                    // 🧠 Why it matters: Clear feedback in Jenkins console about the build version.  
          gv.buildApp()                             // ✅ What it does: Calls buildApp() function from loaded script to run build logic.  
                                                    // 🧠 Why it matters: Keeps build logic modular and reusable outside the Jenkinsfile.  
        }  
      }  
    }  

    stage('Test') {  
      when {  
        expression { return params.executeTests }  // ✅ What it does: Conditionally runs the Test stage only if executeTests is true.  
                                                  // 🧠 Why it matters: Saves build time and resources by skipping tests when not needed.  
      }  
      steps {  
        script {  
          echo "Running tests..."  // ✅ What it does: Logs that tests are running.  
                                   // 🧠 Why it matters: Informative for logs and debugging.  
          gv.testApp()             // ✅ What it does: Calls testApp() function from the external script to run tests.  
                                   // 🧠 Why it matters: Encapsulates test logic outside the Jenkinsfile for maintainability.  
        }  
      }  
    }  

    stage('Deploy') {  
      steps {  
        script {  
          echo "Deploying..."                        // ✅ What it does: Logs a message indicating deployment has started.  
                                                     // 🧠 Why it matters: Provides visual confirmation in console logs.  
          sh "echo Deploying version ${params.VERSION}"  // ✅ What it does: Executes shell command to echo deploy version.  
                                                        // 🧠 Why it matters: Demonstrates integration of shell commands in the pipeline.  
          gv.deployApp()                            // ❗ Issue: deployApp() expects a parameter but none is provided here.  
                                                   // 🧠 Why it matters: Without passing environment, deployment logic may fail or use default.  
        }  
      }  
    }  
  }  
}  

// ✅ NOTES / GOTCHAS / TIPS  
// - The deployApp() function in the external Groovy script expects an argument for environment (e.g., 'dev', 'staging', 'prod').  
// - To fix the pipeline, pass the environment parameter, e.g., gv.deployApp('dev') or add user input to select environment dynamically.  
// - Using 'params.VERSION' inside the Groovy script requires the Jenkinsfile to pass that param or set global access carefully.  
// - For shell commands, ensure the agent environment supports 'sh' (Linux/Mac) or adapt for Windows agents accordingly.  
